<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; SOME DILEMMAS ARE MADE FOR VIDEOTAPING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARRIE ST. MICHEL, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Many situations in life are clear-cut. You know exactly what to do. 
</P>
<P>
 Let's say, for example, you're a professional athlete. Your job, which is 
basically part time, essentially involves a lot of standing around, scratching 
and spitting. For this you are paid, on average, $1.2 million a year. Of 
course, no one should endure such oppressive conditions. You have no choice 
other than to go out on strike. Hardly a tough call. 
</P>
<P>
 Or, say you're the leader of a major world power. Things aren't going all that 
well, though. There's even talk of replacing you with a fellow named Gump. 
Granted, it's probably just the ploy of embittered partisans. But the 
Republicans are rumored to be working on a plan as well. Again, an easy 
decision. With renewed resolve, you plant your feet firmly in, uh, the sand at 
Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
 Unfortunately, there are many other situations that aren't so black-and-white. 
I found myself in such a circumstance just the other day. 
</P>
<P>
 Actually, this situation was black-and-white -- at least the cow was. Here's 
what happened: 
</P>
<P>
 I leave the standard note for the kids -- "Have been abducted by aliens, 
again. Love, Mom" -- and sneak out to the back yard for what I hope will be at 
least three minutes of peace and quiet. So there I am, becoming one with my 
lounge chair, and I see this woman walking what appears to be a rather large 
Holstein. 
</P>
<P>
 No problem, so far. You see, where I live, it's kind of like Venice Beach 
meets the 4-H. It's not at all unusual to see people Rollerblading with their 
goats, jogging with potbellied pigs or babbling incoherently to a gaggle of 
geese. 
</P>
<P>
 So I'm not fazed. But then I see this woman, and her cow, go into a model 
home. You know, the kind they decorate really nicely to distract you from the 
fact that the mortgage will probably bankrupt you, or at best leave you with 
enough money to maybe put a couple of beanbags on layaway. 
</P>
<P>
 My first thought was: I wouldn't really mind being abducted by aliens. Chances 
are it would get me out of making dinner, and I have to think that light-years 
convert to massive frequent-flier miles. 
</P>
<P>
 Maybe they take a few specimens, ask a few questions -- such as: Why is Bruce 
Willis doing nude scenes -- wasn't "Hudson Hawk" embarrassing enough? Is 
"Jurassic Park" out on video yet? And where might we get tickets to see that 
Billy Joel-Elton John concert? 
</P>
<P>
 Geez, I have to learn to focus. Remember: cow, expensive furnishings, nasty 
carpet stains. So what should I do? 
</P>
<P>
 I have to assume it's unwise to start trouble with someone accompanied by a 
thousand-pound pet. For all I know, it could be a trained attack cow. One false 
move and I'm Bossy's in-between-meal snack. 
</P>
<P>
 Or it could be one of those radical farm animals, the kind that will stampede 
your house if they even suspect you own as much as a pair of leather shoelaces. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides, there could be any number of logical explanations. This is the 
country after all. Maybe cattle can become licensed real estate agents. I've 
certainly met plenty who are full of bull . . . well, who were very 
bovine-like. 
</P>
<P>
 It could be that this woman just bought the house and is doing the required 
walk-through accompanied by her keen-eyed, cud-chewing assistant. Or, maybe she 
is considering buying the house and brought along a psychic cow. (Hey, we're 
not that far from L.A.) One moo for "house has good vibes," two moos for "do 
you remember that movie 'Poltergeist?' " 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, it's equally possible that she's the lunatic leader of the lawless 
Guernsey gang that has been stomping through model homes from here to 
Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
 But who to call? The police? The animal shelter? State board of real estate 
brokers? Jerseymaid? 
</P>
<P>
 After much thought, I did what seems to be the standard 1990s response in such 
should-I-or-should-I-not-get-involved situations. I caught it all on videotape. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, where's that number for "Hard Copy"? 
</P>
</TEXT>
