<HEADLINE>
<P>
BULLFROGS' SEMIFINAL SERIES STARTS AT PORTLAND TONIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL ITAGAKI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Bullfrogs open their Western Conference final series tonight against the 
Portland Rage at the Memorial Coliseum in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
 Game 2 of the Roller Hockey International playoff series will be at 7:30 p.m. 
on Tuesday at The Pond of Anaheim.If the teams split the series, a 12-minute 
mini-game will follow Game 2 to decide who will advance to the RHI championship 
series against the Eastern Conference champion, the winner of the 
Buffalo-Minnesota series. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bullfrogs, who won the RHI championship last season, finished the regular 
season losing five of their last six games. But a different team has shown up 
for the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 "I never lost confidence in this team," Bullfrogs Coach Grant Sonier said. 
"During the season, there were times we were very undisciplined and it cost us. 
In the playoffs, we've been focused." 
</P>
<P>
 The Bullfrogs have won four consecutive playoff games, including a two-game 
sweep of the Blades in the Pacific Division finals. 
</P>
<P>
 In the playoffs, Victor Gervais is the Bullfrogs' hot scorer, with a 
league-high 11 goals in four games. 
</P>
<P>
 Goalie Rob Laurie, who struggled in the second half of the season, has 
returned to top form. He has four victories in four playoff starts and leads 
the league in post-season save percentage. Laurie is 7-0 in seven career RHI 
playoff starts. 
</P>
<P>
 Portland is led by forwards Andy Rymsha and Brian Downey, the two top scorers 
in the RHI playoffs with 19 and 17 points. The Rage averaged more than nine 
goals in four playoff games. MICHAEL ITAGAKI 
</P>
